               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18350302-name-974" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18350302-name-974" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18350302-name-974" type="surname" value="PEEK"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18350302-name-974" type="given" value="MATTHEW"></interp>MATTHEW PEEK</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">police-constable C</hi> 198.) On the 20th of February, about eight o'clock at night, I was in Finsbury-market, and saw Nowland come for the loan of a truck—I asked him some questions, and followed him—he took it to Finsbury-square; and I saw in a dark place another truck, broken down, and a hogshead on it—the hogshead was taken off that, and put on another truck, which I followed.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18350302-name-975" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18350302-name-975" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18350302-name-975" type="surname" value="NOWLAND"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18350302-name-975" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>JOHN NOWLAND</persName>
                  </hi>. About eight o'clock that night I saw two men with great-coats on—they had a truck broken down—they asked me to get a truck, which I did, from Finsbury-market; and when I got it, they had got a truck, and got the hogshead of juice on it—I asked who was to pay me—they said they had no money, and I returned home.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18350302-name-976" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18350302-name-976" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18350302-name-976" type="surname" value="GREGORY"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18350302-name-976" type="given" value="THOMAS WALTER"></interp>THOMAS WALTER GREGORY</persName>
                  </hi>. I am in the service of John Lloyd War<lb></lb>dell</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="183503020165"></xptr>
               <p>and another—he had a truck on his premises, which was stolen on the 20th of February—I saw the some truck broken at Worship-street afterwards.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18350302-name-977" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18350302-name-977" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18350302-name-977" type="surname" value="PINNER"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18350302-name-977" type="given" value="GEORGE"></interp>GEORGE PINNER</persName>
                  </hi>. On the 20th of February, the prisoner came to my father's house to borrow a truck—my father said he had not one, but there was a place in Finsbury-market where they lent them, and he sent me with him—I got it, and took it to Finsbury-square, where there was a broken truck with a hogshead of juice on it—there were two men with great-coats on, and the prisoner and another person—they got the hogshead on the truck, and I took the broken truck to Mr. Dickerson's, in Finsbury-market, where I had borrowed the other.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. PHILLIPS</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Did not the two men in great<lb></lb>coats go on with the other truck? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes—I did not hear them give the prisoner any directions, but they spoke to him—they might direct him to go with it.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18350302-name-978" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18350302-name-978" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18350302-name-978" type="surname" value="DICKERSON"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18350302-name-978" type="given" value="PHOEBE"></interp>PHOEBE DICKERSON</persName>
                  </hi>. I had the broken truck brought to my house—I gave it to the officer.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18350302-name-979" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18350302-name-979" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18350302-name-979" type="surname" value="MAYNARD"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18350302-name-979" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>WILLIAM MAYNARD</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">police-constable G</hi> 113.) I received the broken truck—it was claimed by the prosecutor.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Prisoner's Defence.</hi> I had been to Thames-street that evening, and as I was going up Fish-street I saw a truck standing in the street, and a young man with it—there were two gentlemen with great-coats on, who said to me, "If you will lend our man a hand to take this truck, we will pay you"—I assisted him; and when we got to Finsbury-square the truck broke down—they said, "What shall we do?" said I—I knew Mr. Pinner, the cooper, who, perhaps, could lend one—I went to him, and he sent his boy to Finsbury-market, where we got one—we then loaded that truck with the hogshead which was in the broken truck, and they told me to go on to New-inn-yard, which we did, and there the officer stopped us.</p>
               <p>
